<p>Pittsburgh homeowners can expect solar payback periods of 12-15 years based on current electricity rates of 12.8¬¢/kWh and available incentives. A typical 6kW system producing 7,200 kWh annually will save approximately \$922 per year at current rates, assuming 100% self-consumption or net metering credits. Over 25 years, total savings typically range from \$18,000-25,000 after accounting for system costs and the federal tax credit. The internal rate of return usually falls between 6-8%, comparing favorably to many traditional investments. Rising electricity rates improve returns over time, as Duquesne Light rates have increased an average of 2.1% annually over the past decade. Additional benefits include increased property values (typically 4% for homes with solar), energy independence, and reduced carbon footprint. Cold weather actually enhances panel efficiency, with systems often producing 5-10% more electricity in winter months than predicted by standard modeling software, improving overall financial returns for Pittsburgh installations.</p>

